\cf0 There are seven moods: indicative, mirative, assumptive, alethic, renarrative, commissive, and optative.  Mood is shown through the use of prefixes.\
\
INDICATIVE\
Prefix: None\
The indicative mood is used to state factual information, where the speaker is merely relaying knowledge, rather than interpreting information.\
English example: You eat food.\
\
MIRATIVE\
Prefix: \'e4l\'92-\
The mirative mood is used to state unexpected factual information, which the speaker considers especially surprising or important.\
English example: You ate a lot of food!\
\
ASSUMPTIVE\
Prefix: odl\'92-\
The assumptive mood is used to state information that the speaker assumes is true based on previous knowledge, or information that the speaker has deduced from provided evidence.\
English example: You must be hungry.\
\
ALETHIC\
Prefix: dul\'92-\
The alethic mood is used to state information in which no other possible scenario can be true.  It is used primarily in mathematics and logic, and in instances where an idea is so widely accepted that any other possibility is preposterous to even think about.  This mood differs from the indicative because it not only states what occurred, but also that it is the only possible thing to have occurred.\
English example: The food must be digesting.\
\
RENARRATIVE\
Prefix: \uc0\u658 \u257 sl\'92-\
The renarrative mood is used to state information that was learned from someone else, especially if the validity of the information is in question.\
English example: I heard that one shouldn\'92t exercise after eating.\
\
COMMISSIVE\
Prefix: t\'e4dl\'92-\
The commissive mood is used to make promises.\
English example: I promise that I won\'92t exercise yet.\
\
OPTATIVE\
Prefix: uHl\'92-\
The optative mood is used to express a wish (future tense), desire (present tense), or a regret (past tense).\
English examples:\
It will be nice when I can exercise again.\
It would be nice if I could go for a jog right now.\
It would have been nice if I hadn\'92t eaten all of that food.\
