\cf0 The command is used to give direction.  The sentence structure is the same as that for the active voice except for these changes:\
1.  There is no subject to a command\
2.  The first verb (\'93dot\'94) is conjugated with a suffix of \'93-l\'94 (\'93dotl\'94)\
While the prefixes stay the same, there are noticeable changes in mood for command, resulting in five new moods:\
\
IMPERATIVE\
Prefix: Same as indicative\
A basic command, with no connotations placed on it by the speaker.\
English example: Do it.\
\
HORTATIVE\
Prefix: Same as assumptive\
Used to state what one should do.\
English example: You should do it.\
\
JUSSIVE\
Prefix: Same as alethic\
Used to give orders or explain duties.\
English example: You shall do it.\
\
PRECATIVE\
Prefix: Same as commissive\
Used to make requests; used with question marks.\
English example: Will you do it?\
\
PERMISSIVE\
Prefix: Same as optative\
Used to give permission, or show that something is allowed.\
English example: You may do it.\
\
The mirative and renarrative moods cannot be used with commands.{\*\}}